Introduction

In this notebook, we visualize the coronavirus situation in Finland. We use a dataset acquired from the Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare and use the tidyverse and ggmap packages to manipulate and visualize the data. The ggmap package uses the Google Maps API, so it is necessary to sign up to the Google Cloud Platform to be able to access the API. The full source code is available at the projects GitHub repository.

Data Preparation

Lets get started by importing our data. The Google Cloud Platform API key is stored in our home directory in a â.Renvironâ file, so you need to create that file as well, or directly copy and paste the API key as a string to the api_key variable in R.

api_key <- Sys.getenv("GOOGLE_MAPS")
covid1 <- read_csv2("./data/covid19case.csv")

Lets take a look at our data.

It seems that our date column is formatted badly so we need to reformat it to a more structured representation. We first split the âAikaâ column with separate (which is in finnish and means time) and then we combine the âyearâ and âweekâ columns into a one column named âdateâ and convert it to a date object. After that we rename the columns and drop all rows with missing values.

covid2 <- covid1 %>%
  separate(Aika, c("y", "year", "w", "week"), sep =" ") %>%
  select(-y, -w) %>%
  unite(date, c(year, week), sep = "") %>%
  mutate(date = paste(date, "04", sep = "")) %>%
  transmute(date = as.Date(date, "%Y%U%w"), area = Alue, cases = val) %>%
  filter(!is.na(cases), !is.na(date))

Exploratory Analysis

Now that we have our data cleaned, we start to examine our data more in depth. Lets start by summarising the data. The below output summarises the total covid-19 cases by different areas.

As we can see, the first area âKaikki Alueetâ (All Areas) counts the covid-19 cases in all of the areas. We will need to remove those values for the following steps we have. It also seems that the Helsinki area has clearly the most covid-19 cases in all of the areas. Lets plot the total covid-19 cases in the top 5 areas.

## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
## Selecting by total_cases

This plot confirms the notion that the Helsinki area has the most significant exposure to covid-19. Lets have a look how the covid-19 cases have developed with the passage of time.

As we can see, the covid-19 cases have exploded after October 2020 in all of the areas, most notably in the Helsinki area. As a final step, lets put the covid-19 cases on a map to have a better view where exactly the covid-19 has spread. We use the ggmap package to draw the map, which is built on top of the ggplot2 package. We have also built a new tibble that has additional columns representing the latitude and longitude coordinates of the different areas in the top 5 areas, so that we can plot the total cases on the map.

# area coordinates
coordinates_HUS <- c(24.943536799, 60.166640739)
coordinates_PS <- c(23.761290078, 61.497742570)
coordinates_PPS <- c(25.472099070, 65.013784817)
coordinates_VS <- c(21.615874122, 63.092588875)
coordinates_VSS <- c(22.266866666, 60.451690351)
# center point coordinates (JyvÃ¤skylÃ¤)
coordinates_center <- c(lon = 25.72088, lat = 62.24147)

lon <- c(coordinates_HUS[1], 
         coordinates_PS[1],
         coordinates_PPS[1], 
         coordinates_VS[1],
         coordinates_VSS[1])

lat <- c(coordinates_HUS[2], 
         coordinates_PS[2],
         coordinates_PPS[2], 
         coordinates_VS[2],
         coordinates_VSS[2])

covid5  <- covid3 %>% add_column(lon, lat)

map <- ggmap(get_googlemap(coordinates_center, zoom = 6))
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=62.24147,25.72088&zoom=6&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&key=xxx
map + 
  geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, size = total_cases), 
             data = covid5, 
             color = "blue", 
             alpha = 0.5
             ) +
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        axis.title = element_blank(),
        axis.text = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(5, 30))
